{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5c977a17-652b-45fe-b5b4-b95b20211ce4","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe project and report confirm the bottleneck is **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation**, not compilation itself. Visual Studio avoids this because it keeps MSBuild nodes and the Roslyn compiler server alive in-process.\n\nBy default, `dotnet build` sets `/nodeReuse:false`, meaning every invocation cold-starts MSBuild. Here are concrete fixes:\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop (biggest win)\nEliminates process restart entirely:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build          # rebuilds on file change\ndotnet watch run            # rebuilds and re-runs\n```\n\n### 2. Enable MSBuild Server (`.NET 7+`)\nKeeps a long-lived MSBuild process warm between CLI invocations:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build   # first build warms up; subsequent builds reuse the server\n```\n\n### 3. Enable node reuse\nKeeps MSBuild worker nodes alive between builds:\n```bash\ndotnet build -nodeReuse:true\n# or set permanently:\nexport MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0\n```\n\n### 4. Enable shared Roslyn compilation in the project\nThis ensures the Roslyn compiler server (`VBCSCompiler`) stays resident, avoiding compiler cold-start when actual recompilation is needed:\n\n```xml\n<UseSharedCompilation>true</UseSharedCompilation>\n```\n\nFor a quick permanent setup, developers can add to their shell profile:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\nexport MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0\n```\n\n**Recommended combo**: `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` + `dotnet watch` gives a VS-like experience from the terminal.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c7cd6f4d-0527-4b01-8004-2194592eb86d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow (2-4 seconds) even for no-op builds, while Visual Studio builds nearly instantly. They've verified:\n- No analyzers are slowing things down\n- Incremental build targets work correctly (targets skip)\n- Compilation itself is <500ms\n\nThe overhead is from MSBuild process startup and project graph re-evaluation on every CLI invocation.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses a persistent MSBuild server process that keeps the project graph loaded in memory, avoiding cold-start overhead. The CLI equivalent of this is the **MSBuild Server** (also called the MSBuild node reuse / MSBuild server).\n\n\nTo address this, I can enable the MSBuild server to keep the process alive between builds—either through the `dotnet build-server` command or by setting environment variables like `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`. For iterative development workflows, `dotnet watch` would be even more effective since it maintains a single running process across multiple builds.\n\nThe real issue is that the CLI disables node reuse by default (`/nodeReuse:false`), spawning a fresh MSBuild process each time, whereas Visual Studio keeps those nodes in memory and maintains the Roslyn compiler server running continuously.\n\nTo match VS performance, I should enable node reuse with `/nr:true` or set `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=0`, use `dotnet watch` for hot rebuilds, and in .NET 7+ enable the MSBuild server with `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` to avoid cold-start penalties. Adding the Roslyn compiler server setting to the project file...","outputTokens":1394,"requestId":"280C:12EB87:5C189A2:638AA80:69FBE1DD"},"id":"bcc5a1be-f260-4532-b901-eb6da0f8926f","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:51:05.259Z","parentId":"2b1fc183-5bfa-4df7-a117-bcfe4b5b1d0d"}
